  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use homotopy equivalence only when you can provide maps and homotopies showing they are inverses up to homotopy.\n¶Definitions A map f:X→Yf:X \\to Y is a homotopy equivalence if there exists g:Y→Xg:Y \\to X such that:\ng∘f≃idX,f∘g≃idY. g \\circ f \\simeq \\mathrm{id}_X,\\quad f \\circ g \\simeq \\mathrm{id}_Y. ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Inverse up to homotopy: not strictly inverse, but equivalent by deformation. ¶Symbols used ≃\\simeq: homotopic. idX\\mathrm{id}_X: identity map on XX. ¶Intuition Homotopy equivalence says two spaces are the same \u0026ldquo;shape\u0026rdquo; from the perspective of homotopy, even if they are not homeomorphic.\n",
